messages.content: **1. Introduction**
Joliene Swansong wakes up in her bed. It is still dark, both inside and outside. It is earlier than she would likely normally wake up. What will she do? Roll perception.
She rolls perception yeah.
There is someone in her room.

This doesn't process as unusual to her immediately, thanks to some combination of drowsiness and living with two (effectively three) other people. Though, the figure being clouded in the shadows was certainly not inviting. Why was it still dark, anyway? "Bruno?"
‚ÄúUh,‚Äù This is not a voice she recognizes.
What the fuck.
"What the fuck!?"
‚ÄúFuck.‚Äù The room lights up a little from the use of magic. Roll for initiative! üôÇ

The interloper prepares in his hand, but does not fire, a fireball. ‚ÄúH-hey, I don‚Äôt want any trouble, I‚Ä¶‚Äù

This is his turn.

It‚Äôs @Joliene Swansong!

Joliene does not have any weaponry in arm's reach of where she sleeps, but her muscle memory tells her to spring into action regardless. She fumbles off her bed with a gravelly grunt and makes a mad crawl for one of the tables, which she has a whip on.
This is her turn.
"What are you doing in my house!? Eric! Bonnell! Get out! Intruder!"

‚ÄúEeaagh!‚Äù He fires off the fireball but misses you. A portion of the room is still on fire.

Suddenly, an old man you have also never seen before breaks in through the fucking window. ‚ÄúGotcha.‚Äù He sets his sights on the original intruder.

It‚Äôs @Joliene Swansong!

She readies her whip, but then nearly collapses even further when her window shatters. She repeats "what the fuck" until her throat goes hoarse, but is still lucid enough to recognize the current biggest threat to her life long-term is the fire.

So, she flail-cracks the whip at the fire in an attempt to put it out.

This works, somehow. 

Bonnell slams open the door brandishing a knife. ‚ÄúWHAT THE HELL IS GOING ON HERE!?‚Äù

The old man ignores him and rushes straight for the first guy, impaling him through the chest. The first guy uses his turn to collapse onto the ground.

It‚Äôs @Joliene Swansong!

Joliene wheezes grotesquely for a triad of reasons, consisting of the smoke, physical exertion, and her grander condition. She then readies her whip once more, but does nothing except stare blankly at whatever the fuck is happening here.

Bonnell misses.

The old man flees, moving faster than any normal person should be able to.

Combat has ended.

‚ÄúEh?‚Äù Bonnell.
Slack-jawed, she scans the room, particularly the body in front of her. Her reaction is to cough repeatedly, and then fall limp in unsightly sobs, nose against the ground.

‚ÄúGod, this city‚Äôs going to hell in a hand basket! W-what is this, some gang thing? Can‚Äôt they do this on their own time? I can‚Äôt imagine you have anything to do with this, Jo.‚Äù

The bleeding out guy coughs.

Joliene ignores her husband.

"...You." She barely squeezes that out and aims it at the straggling invader. "Who... what..."
((god dammit i should like have a fucking timer of how long i've left someone waiting))
((this is built in to discord))

The intruder struggles to say words through blood. Bonnell does whatever the hell equates to contacting the authority at this tech level.

"S...So..." He dies of blood loss.

I assume that would mean going to the guard's station and telling them what happened. Great. She was going to tell him to do that anyway.

So. She contemplates this syllable for half a second before frustratedly deciding that, much like the rest of her life, this is impossible to make sense of.

She shambles towards her wheelchair and hoists herself in, shaking heavily. Going back to sleep isn't an option any more. She waits in silence.

Morning proper arrives. She‚Äôs pushed out of her room by authorities conducting an initial investigation. Legumi, a person present, makes a ‚Äúwhat can ya do‚Äù expression and asks what the fuck happened.
(who the fuck is Legumi)
guy named legumi

Joliene has been part of the guard long enough to know this will probably become a Big Ongoing Thing. Legumi's presence at least gives her a scrap of hope that it'll be painless.

"I woke up in the middle of the night, and the dead guy was standing in my room. He wasn't dead yet. Just... watching me sleep." She sighs, and takes a long pause. "Then another guy broke through my window and killed him. Then he left. That's basically it."
:livesongpc:
"Well, alright. Hopefully getting your side of the story early will prevent them from being too anal about this."
"One can hope." She runs her palms down her face. "Goddamnit..."

After a minute or so of uninterrupted silence, she sees fit to elaborate: "I don't have the slightest idea who either of them are, or why the other guy thought he'd find the dead one in my room. It's total fucking nonsense. Surely this wasn't a common thing when I was still active..."

"Yeah, this is just... inane. The perp gets killed by another unidentified guy? God."

A guy comes around and mumbles something to Legumi. She talks back for a bit and rolls her eyes. "Something's even more screwed about this case. They want you out of your own house, sorry. And apparently *I'm* not good enough to stay involved. We should be free to do whatever as long as you don't skip town, you up for drinks?"

"They already have enough to go off to classify it and kick me out of my own home?" Frowning deeply, she shakes her head. "Wonderful. Just what I needed. Hopefully the guard's still smart enough to realize an invalid isn't in any position to stab a guy and dispose of the weapon. A drink's the only thing that could possibly take my mind off this shit..."
Legumi smiles, very politely enabling your bad habits. The two successfully arrive at [BAR], featuring [BARTENDER like in Q&A].

Gotta love the familiar aroma of non-specific fantasy alcohol. Probably ale. She hoists herself onto the bar stool and lets the bartender prepare her drink, being enough of a regular for him to intuit she only ever gets tall mugs of the aforementioned ale.
Yes this does happen 100% true it does occur. Legumi asks how you've been, making some incredible small talk.

Joliene, for emphasis, repeats everything she told her at home, then grumbles incoherently about her general situation. "It's just awful. All of it. A creep breaks into my house, and what saves me is somebody else doing the same thing. What the hell was *I* supposed to do? Whip him away from the floor? Fetch my fucking archery kit, an entire room away? God forbid, call for *Bonnell?* The guy couldn't hit him with a knife, and he was impaled to the *fucking* floor!" She takes a swig. Her rants are not usually this impassioned.
Especially before she's been drinking.

Legumi nods. "It's a hell of a start to the day. The guy could've had the decency to stick around." She remembers that this was a real visibly murdering person and corrects herself. "...Not to keep doing insane shit, I mean. Just... who the hell does that and then leaves???" She poorly takes a sip of her drink, serving as a deep societal commentary on the fact that glasses are not designed with the mouths of bird people in mind.

[Paragraph removed because I‚Äôm boredom-rereading things at five in the morning and I‚Äôm only now realizing that I totally misread one of the sentences above, and never got corrected. Fucked up. It‚Äôs not even a recton, because it‚Äôs just wacky fourth-wall-breaking narration anyway. I think I just wanted to use the word pince-nez.]

"Most murderers don't linger around the crime scene for long, shockingly. I'd love to back the guy up as justified in defending me, but there's so obviously more to this crime that I'm reluctant to take a stance."

She drinks again, downing half the glass in one go. "I can't keep going like this any more. It'd be so much with everything else going on now, but... I've been thinking about getting divorced."
Legumi sighs. "Mm. I can't say the signs weren't there. I always thought it was weird, anyway, that you two... well, it's not my place. I hope the kid can end up okay."
"...Eric's practically raised by the state anyway. He'll be fine." She ignores her comments about the oddity of their relationship, simply drinking more. "I have a headache..."

Legumi, rolling a natural 20 in perception, begins to wonder if this might be unhealthy, but her interjection is interrupted by the arrival of Head Of Guard Dale Marshland. "Do you have a minute, jojo?" He has not used this nickname before, and it objectively sucks.

Joliene's head perks, and because reality is subjective, she immediately takes to the nickname. Unusual, though. "I was just wondering about you, actually. I can't remember the last time I *didn't* have a minute. This is about the... the home invasion-slash-murder, yeah?"

"Ehhhhhh." He makes a non-commital noise that is neither yes nor no. "I..." He looks over at Legumi. "I guess it doesn't really matter if you hear." 

She shrugs and leaves regardless.

"I'm sure you've been asked a billion times already, but I'm supposed to check; you don't know either of the men you saw, right?" (Dale)

She neglected to mention that she hadn't been asked that once. "It was dark, so I couldn't really make out any of their features. Their voices weren't familiar, though. Sure as can be on that. What, did you identify the dead guy already?"

"Ehhhhhhhhh. Surprising as it might be, I'm kinda here for a reason that doesn't have anything to do with that. Are you familiar with the elite guard? Y'know, people posted directly in important government sites or places of interest."
The puts the back of her hand under her chin in thought. "Haven't heard of the term before, no, but it's simple to assume something like that exists."

"Yeah, the bottom line is that Joliene Swansong specifically has been requested to head to the capital effective immediately." He scratches his head. "I swear, I don't understand any more than you do."

The half-orc purses her lips skeptically for a moment. "Some title Head of the Guard turned out to be, huh? Wonder what the reason is for keeping you in the dark." Polishing off the last of her ale, she turns around and maneuvers back into her wheelchair. "Not like I can ignore this. Care to push me there? I'm sure you understand why I don't feel like exerting myself right now."

"Yeah, alright. I arranged for transport and everything, let your family know, so unless you have anything you want to finish up in Arenda, we can head out. Again, real sorry. I really did think they'd fucking tell me what's going on with this sort of thing now."

She gives him a glance and a shrug to demonstrate her sympathy. She considers heading to the town hall and filing for divorce, but doesn't know enough about it to decide if she can get that out of the way fast enough. "We can go."

They do go this happens. It's a decently long commute. A guy apologizes before vaguely moving his hands around you, muttering that its standard procedure and yeah you're clean. He directs you to the entrance of specifically the royal palace to which Dale does the cereal guy second panel. "Uh, okay. Let's... go? Hot diggity." He is unequipped for understanding what is going on in TAP.

((I think this is probably the best place to leave off for now lol but you are not done a chapter or anything I just have not prepared for this and do not think there will be a better point to leave off))
((lmao fine with me))
Joliene.
Joliene.
She looks up to get a feel for the full scope of the palace, stone-faced. "You're coming in too, Dale?"

"I guess so."

He is intercepted by a pasty ass white guy wearing a cloak. "No. You were only to escort her here. Please leave."

"Oh, come on. Can I not do anything???"

"...I figured." She gives him a shrug, offering whatever her sympathy meant to him. "Sorry. I can handle myself from here anyway." She waves him off, then puts her hands down to the wheels and spins them in the direction of where it looks like she's supposed to go.
She is escorted by cloak guy. "I am Solnit. I already know your name, don't bother. I'm not one for pleasantries."
She vaguely grunts in acknowledgement.
"It would be better for you to hear from the person most informed on this, anyway." After some amount of walking through hallways, he gestures to a large door.
If the door is some sort of open passageway, she rolls through without a further word. Otherwise, she sort of just sits around with an expectant glare.
It is the latter. Solnit rolls his eyes and opens it with exaggerated flair.

"What an honor." This is only half-sarcastic. She still holds a significant amount of respect for the kingdom.

She moves through yup

The door closes behind her. It becomes clear this is some sort of dining hall. Both the heads of the (rather long) table are empty, and sitting on one of the sides is a woman. Opposite her is some pieces of paper, in the only space at the table without a chair there.

At closer inspection, it becomes clear that this woman is Zita Praxis, queen of the land of Arctica. No way
((Zita Praxis?!!?! Queen of the land of Artica?!!?? What the hell))
This isn't shocking actually.
(( :cereal2: ))
Joliene smiles as a courtesy, shuffling around the table and slotting into her kindly-defined Seating Zone. "You have business with me?" she says before going over the papers.

"...Yes. With several layers of clarification, but that's the gist of it. This is a job interview, or equivalent. You have been recommended directly before. Though it was only the word of the militant general that officially summoned you. You can ask him questions later if you desire; he should be here."

She pauses to drink tea.

"I know the nature of your arrival may send a bad message, so I'll be clear in saying that we are not forcing you to do anything. But for only a short period of employ, you will gain the means to live and provide for yourself indefinitely. There are benefits worth considering."

"For myself, you say?" She raises a brow and continues looking over the documents, clearing her throat quietly. "...Excuse my brevity. I never thought you were one of the royals who actually... did things. I'd also like to skip asking the general questions entirely. May I ask what there's left to see in me at this point?"

She pauses at your question.
"I don‚Äôt care about whatever disadvantages you have. I will not discount you for them, nor will I be overly lenient. What matters is your ability to do the task provided, and your character. I have been assured of the former. The latter is what I am here to ascertain."

"What are your thoughts... on flour?" She is deathly serious.

"...What? I don't bake, and it tastes disgusting. If you think I have anything more to add, you must be mistaking me for somebody else." Joliene has no fucking clue how this is supposed to reflect on her character.
Zita is troubled by this response. "...Okay. You're really not supposed to eat it, you know. The idea is that it's part of a greater whole. In a developmental--it doesn't really matter."
She sighs. "Even if we cannot see eye to eye, you have conviction in your values. If you are willing to accept, I welcome you to this short term position in the elite guard."

She ignores the bit about flour consumption. She didn't eat it in a show of inexperience, but Zita obviously didn't care.

"I try. Conviction alone doesn't protect the population, though. What do you see me fit to guard in this state?" Her tone is genuinely hopeful.

"...To be truthful, I personally don't entirely understand why you were called here. The motives of others are unknown to me. But that's only in regards to us already having capable hands. I believe you undersell yourself, Joliene. There is much more in this world than physical ability, even when looking only at power. You possess... a *je ne sais quoi*. I believe it is not an accident for you to have arrived here."

Yeah, it literally wasn't. She was called. Joliene did not voice this.

"I appreciate the praise. Really, I do. But I would appreciate it if you'd tell me what you want me to do here. I've already got so much on my plate, with the break-in, and the other thing, and... yeah. I can't handle another unknown."

"Break-in?" She tilts her head. "In any case, your day to day actions will involve a shift as lookout in a fortified tower. We can provide ranged weaponry, but you may also bring your own after it is inspected. I have the sense that there's something else, but this is all I'm concretely aware of."

"...A stationary sentry." She smiles genuinely. "Smart. I already own a bow and arrow, but it's hobbyist-grade, so I'll take whatever the kingdom provides... and yes, that means I'm taking the offer." Not like she has much else to do. "Where do I sign?"

Zita leans over, and, realizing the table is too wide for that, instead fucking teleports to your side.
"This paper." She puts her hand on one, and uses her other hand to grab the rest. "The others don't matter, it's just... it's more followups to the flour thing, I had different expectations. Welcome aboard. You'll have a room to sleep in not far from your post. It involves ascending vertically, but... well, we've got someone to deal with that issue. Please, follow me." She move
"Wonderful." She quickly jots her name down on the contract, then MOVES in the SAME DIRECTION as THE QUEEN.
They reach the ""corner"" of the palace. There is a small platform (preceded by a ramp) sizable enough for like two Jolienes. The Queen gestures towards it. "Arctican engineering at its finest."

"What the fuck."

She's absolutely flabbergasted by the existence of the ramp, her arms working furiously to roll up it and onto the platform. "You made this? Just for me? Like... stairs, but only the one, and my wheels can't get caught on it?"

She nods. "Just today. We've got some kind of super-genius working with the royal family recently."

It goes UP when she is fully on it, stopping at where the stairs end (a railing has been visibly removed to allow for you to get there). Zita runs up the stairs. "I couldn't believe it myself."

"WHAT"

She couldn't believe what was happening. A piece of the floor that moved up?? It was unthinkable. She could move up storeys without any assistance. Reminiscent of when the wheelchair was first invested, she was getting emotional. "This is all too much..."

"It's a little convoluted to make right now, so I doubt we'll see widespread use for quite some time. But still! This sort of thing would've been unthinkable in my youth." Zita is close to equally enthused by the concept of an elevator.

"God." Rolling off the elevation device, she turns her head back in an elated chuckle. "Your engineer deserves a pay raise, really. It's incredible how far he's willing to go for one poor edge case." Satisfied, she continues moving, looking for her room.

She does have a room. It's not too big because of the limitations of Tower Space, but it has basic essentials like a bed and dresser.
Zita peeks in. "There's another one of those things between this level and your post. You won't officially start until tomorrow, so you're free to do whatever moving you need for the time being."

"I would've liked some warning before I left so I could bring my effects." She presses a hand down into the mattress, as if to gauge its comfiness. "...I guess I'll have to tell my family in-person before the job starts anyways. Okay. Lead the way to my post."
She does so. This time they BOTH use the platform at the SAME TIME and it STILL works.

"That chest should contain the basics for ranged defense. There's a telescope in there too. This torch here is to be lit as a signal of approaching enemies. You'll figure more out when you start proper, this really isn't an area I have knowledge in."

"Understandable." Standard stuff for keeping watch in the long-term. She's never had to do it in such a rigid environment, though. "Thank you so much for this opportunity, Your Highness. I just-... I need a moment. I'll head back to my village after that to prepare."

Zita stares into the middle distance. "Oh, shit! I mean, um, yes. I have business to attend to as well. I will see you later. Feel free to ask any servants around for assistance, they should not be busy today." She runs off.

"...Yeah."

She has her moment. It comes and goes. Once that's over, she exits the palace and doesn't ask the servants for anything. It's the carriage straight back to Arenda, baby.
Yup it is (she makes it to that place)
THEN..... she goes back to her House.,
who there
Bonnell and Eric Swansong, from TAP
She consciously aims her vacant stare in her husband's direction. "So. I got a job offer in the capital."
"Is that so. That's unusual." He's filling out some papers (He works as an accountant)
"I'm taking it. They have a room set up for for me there. I need help moving."
"Mm." He jots some more words down and then cracks his knuckles. "Fine. What are you bringing, then. And when can I expect you back?"

"Just... a few personal things. Clothes. My old melee weapons. The big horse painting on my wall. Maybe some more things I haven't thought of. There's not a chance I can carry all that in one trip, so..." She gestures in conclusion. "I haven't been given a time frame yet, but we'll see each other again soon. It starts tomorrow."

"...Alright. There's some boxes in the closet, we can probably use them for easier transport." He goes to get the boxes. 
((I do not know how to roleplay an entire moving van. we can either skip through this or just have conversation happen throughout))
"...I would really appreciate it if you went to the capital yourself and moved my things ahead of me. I still have business here, and it'd be a waste to take the carriage any more than I have to."
Joliene is testing Bonnell's patience a little, but he acquiesces. She is alone in her home for now. Except for the kid named eric who never left how could i forget

"Eric." She looks at Eric. "Stay strong, alright?" She pats Eric on the head, then leaves for the bar. If neither Legumi or Dale is still there, she goes to wherever the hell she think they'd be next.
They are BOTH there why not its a more reasonable time of day to be drinking now

"Uh... hey, Legumi. Hey Dale. That thing. The one in the capital that neither of you knew shit about. It was a job offer." She scratches her nape. "I thought you deserved to know. Just... let the guard know I'm not running from the charges they may still want to stick on me."

Dale sighs in relief. "Fuckin' ovan, that's all? Could they have been more ominous about wanting to pay you?"

Legumi looks up from attempting to fashion some kind of funnel to allow her to drink beverages better. "Also, you're not going to jail, Joliene, you goof. The investigation sells your combat abilities shorter than you do, and there's secondhand accounts backing up the Old Man Theory. They did stumble a bit with the motive, though."

"Yeah, I... I had a feeling. I just don't want them getting the wrong idea. I'm happy the problem's solving itself, at least." She sighs.

"...That's it. I'd love to hang around more, but I have *obligations* to attend to now. An actual fucking guard job. Who would've thought." With that, she's off. One more stop: the town hall.
Her friends say their farewells yeah. She arrives at the place she wants to be it is the town hall

Joliene rolls up to the receptionist.

"A divorce. Er... if I wanted to get one of those, how would it... work?"

She pauses. "That is to say, do I just sign a piece of paper and have it done with? Or is there an arduous process?"

The Receptionist, who is now an official character, replies. ‚ÄúWell, ideally the other person would be here. But obviously that‚Äôs not always going to happen, so there‚Äôs still legal paths that involve just you initiating.‚Äù She starts rustling through papers. ‚ÄúThis should really be done at the town courthouse, technically, but we‚Äôre short staffed, so the receptionist there would also be me. Hiding this fact to have you show up there and be met with me rushing in at the same time wouldn‚Äôt really be funny enough to justify the time.‚Äù
She pulls out one form in particular. ‚ÄúYou and your husband‚Äôs name would be a start.‚Äù
"Right, right." She nods along carefully. "I'm Joliene, with an I before the first E, and my husband's name is Bonnell. Er... family name Swansong."

‚ÄúThanks. I was pretty sure, but you never know. I‚Äôve been around for widespread trends almost as weird as wheeled chairs.‚Äù She jots the names down, in addition to a few other details. ‚ÄúIf I send this on its way through the bureaucracy, your husband will find out in around 24 hours. I‚Äôd personally recommend informing him before then.‚Äù She places it into an envelope. ‚ÄúThe answer to your question is that it‚Äôs the second thing. This will be a substantial time investment in the story of your life. You‚Äôre sure about this? I can handle the initial steps, but I can also tear this up now with your confidentiality ensured.‚Äù

"Shit," she mutters under her breath. "...Yeah. Yeah, I'm sure. I'll... let him know about things before it gets to that. I just can't be around signing documents all day. I'm busy. If it has to be like that, I'll deal with it later."
‚ÄúGodspeed, then.‚Äù The Receptionist goes off to her own thrilling campaign of walking and doing paperwork. Such is the life of a public servant.
And so it is done.
Joliene sits there for half a minute in silence before taking the next carriage back to Imperviat.
She does this. From the perspective of narration, time is immaterial. She arrives.
Straight back to her new room.
One elevator later, she is in there.
Is all the stuff she asked Bonnell to bring there?
More or less, sure.
Okay. She goes to bed.
Bed success

It also wouldn't be surprising if she didn't, weirdly enough.

Big day ahead for Jo. She's *employed* now, for the first time since first getting crippled. She starts her day by crawling into her wheelchair, finding a change of clothes (potentially the standard for the royal guard?) and sits around while waiting for further instructions. Her outlook is optimistic.

She's able to do all of these things.

The Gfucking Queen, who apparently has nothing better to do, arrives with two cups of coffee.

"Good morning."

A prominently-fanged smile is bared to her employer, and she takes the coffee as it's offered to her. She doesn't even like the drink, bit sips it for politeness's sake. "Good morning to you too, Your Highness. Or is there a title you'd prefer?"
She laughs. "Just Zita is fine. I'm not the Queen until I've been awake for at least a half hour, anyway."

"Hah, you're just like me."

"...minus the position. Ahem. Zita." She could get used to this, perhaps. "Once again, I'm happy to be of service. Am I supposed to be on post as soon as I wake up?"

"That's why I'm here. I realized I never actually told you that part. The policy is to always have at least one entrance lookout posted at a time, and there are three towers that have a view of the front. There's two others with a similar position to you, one in the opposite corner and one closer to the center." None of these details actually matter. "The point is, you needn't be alert 24/7. The hours we're expecting from you are [relatively normal like 9 to five workday no fucking way], during which you'll spend as much time as possible atop the tower, and absolutely not stray from the areas accessible via lifts bar some kind of emergency. ...Merl should still be on watch right about now, so you've got a half hour to yourself."
((this is it. this is the only individual in all of TAP who will be named Merl. savor it.))

Oh, yeah. Her working hours. She figured those would be on the contract, the fine details of which she only skimmed, so she's relieved Zita offered those up on her own. "Yeah. Staying in my assigned area... won't be difficult, short of a miracle. Maybe that's why you hired me," she half-joked. "Getting used to things will be a little *odd*, all things considered. It's a lifestyle change, but one for the better."
She smiles. "I'm glad. I've been led to understand you're a family woman, and I hate to take you away from that for a brief period, but I hope they understand."

"That's... yup." She gives her a thumbs up. This is the first time she's ever done this for anyone in her entire life. "My reputation precedes me. I'm glad. Do you know how long the job will last yet?"
"I checked yesterday. It's two weeks. You should probably ask around for the specifics when you have the time, though, I'm still only half-informed."
"...If not even you're fully informed, then who am I supposed to ask? The King?"

She chuckles. "Well, he might know, but I'm afraid he has much more on his plate than I do. It's lovely talking to you, Joliene, but there are laws to pass and subordinates to placate for my husband. I'd ask his brother, Frank. He sent out the order for your presence. The Eastern Advisor, Virtos Dextrum, also seemed to know something about you. He's a little... vague. When you ask him things. But he might be of assistance."

The general upwards curl of her lips that persisted this morning began to wilt. "Oh... right. You said something like that before." She was in good hands, clearly. She made an effort to keep her tone consistent and continued: "Well, I don't think it's likely the contract will be extended past two weeks anyways. I'll savour it while I can."
She smiles, finishing her coffee. "I'll see you around, then." Then fcuking LEAVES

messages.content:
**MBMJ strides towards the familiar guy and outstretches his hand.**

"Hello, Lady, Layton, or Theyton, I am Mr. Big Man Jr., and while Big is in my name, I'm just a small-time protector of justice and wrestling in this fine world. I am elated to formally meet someone I've seen around in my love-nest." **He gestures around to the room, and then to the whole building around him.**

"Yeah. Uh, okay." Walt responds first.
"Glad to have you!" Bruna.

**MBMJ gives a wide grin to Walt and Bruna before sitting down.**

"Sorry for holding up the proceedings, but I can't let us proceed without getting my holdings in order, and by holdings I specifically mean the hearts and minds I hold within my cranial tube. You all can go ahead- I understand this meeting is most likely not about me, and it is my humble presence that can just weigh in as a voice of justice."

The somewhat familiar man puts up his hand in a "really, it's alright" pose, cruelly denying the handshake. "And what, uh, role does *he* serve here, specifically?"

Bruna looks at him like he just asked if he could cripple a baby. "That's... Mr. Big Man Jr."
Docker says words next. "It's financial woes, lad. This here fella's wantin' to know what we do here."
"It's okay, Bruna. If someone is not immediately wowed by my radiant aura, that isn't their fault for wielding dull eyes, but instead mine, for mishandling my aura-"
"Ah- ah."
**MBMJ gulps.**

**MBMJ puts his head down, and taps on the table a few times.** "If anybody else would like to expound upon our art, they can feel free to do so, but if my input is valued, well, I suppose I could do some expounding, or even exclobbering, myself..."
((sorry there is. way more franticness elsewhere as you can probably surmise lol))

"Does he only go by that? Is this like the orphan killer guy or whatever?" Vaguely familiar man. "Whatever. I'm Cent Ageny. Head of the entertainer's guild. Your boss's boss."

Walt does look a little on edge. He's a nervous guy in general so it can be tricky to tell.

"My name is Mr. Big Man Jr." **MBMJ hangs his head down before raising his head up and looking Ageny in the eyes.** "There might be someone else, somewhere else, a long way away. But here? This is serious. Killer serious. *Justice* serious. There can't be any slip-ups. No cracks. I am good at what I do. Here, I am Mr. Big Man Jr. It has to be that way. Do you understand?"
"No, not at all. This... *sport*, it involves a large amount of violence, yes? But not to a lethal extent."

"A sport?" **MBMJ shakes his head and looks at the other people in the room.** "Seems some poor sop has put some wool over your eyes. I'll de-sheepify you." **He points at The Early Bird.**"You know him, right? He's crossed over. A star- he's into all those shows, the stage, and he's excellent at it too- a radiant lake of lava, shining over everything. A sunny bird. Other people from other, well, 'sports,' might show up in places, but none of them have truly become... well..." **He points at the Early Bird again.**

"That should be the hint in your brain. The stage out there is a lot closer to what we do than any other 'sport.'  They're two adjacent brothers. Different, but the same. The sport is a side effect. It's the frame we use to do what we do. The stage, poetry, all of that, it's implosion. What we do out there, it's explosion. On the stage, they offer vignettes. Windows into different worlds."

**He clears his throat.**

"We don't deal in windows here. It's continuous. We *are* a..." **He struggles to speak.** "A different world. We show them something through this frame you've given us. There are good guys, there are bad guys, there are friendships, there are betrayals. We have done, well, how many presentations, all in series, in the last several years?" **He looks at Walt.** "An uncountable amount. More than the sand on a beach. More than the stars in the sky. And we've done it all with different little shiny things. Romance, Comedy, Tragedy, Drama... it's all here. And it's *real.* It happens. Look at me. Gaze upon me with your sullen eyes I *am* Mr. Big Man Jr."

"When someone else has a feud in a play, it's play. Here, it is fought. With blood. With magic. They portray the world. We *are* the world.

And that is all *on top of* the sport. Physical strength, technique, magic, endurance..."

**MBMJ stands up.**

"You say it involves violence, but, well, the focus is different. Your mind's eye is askew. To say that we are about the violence is like to say that opera is about the singing. To do so misses the point. But we're not opera... we're... ballet.

We're ballet with violence."

Bruna softly claps and stops, realizing nobody else is.

Cent Ageny just kind of sat there making the live Tucker Reaction.

The Early Bird, currently out of costume as real self Bennett Egret, strokes his chin thoughtfully.

"Aye. And it's plenty profitable! Stadium was packed the other day, it was."
"I... I don't know the financials. I just know what we do."

"The turnout isn't everything. How much did you have to decrease ticket prices by for that?"

Walt shrivels up like a turtle.

"Yes, you're breaking even, fine. But this guild has given a *lot* of assistance to you for little return. I report directly to the crown, you know. There's a lot of pressure about respecting the culture of our land."
**MBMJ furrows his eyebrow at Ageny.** "Were my ears correct in telling me you find what we do here offensive to 'the culture of our land'?"
"I didn't say that, you did. I have received some pressure from those who consider this a hallowed tradition. And it does date back far, yes."

"Then I suppose you understand- this is a long and storied tradition. It has had value for ages, it's been with our people for a long time, and it is still going strong. I have seen many ideas, many thoughts succeed and fail in wrestling, and it belongs to me as it belongs to wrestlers hundreds of years ago. There is a reason why it hasn't died out until now. It's an unbroken chain of practice. What would it say if it were nipped now, like the testes of some unruly animal?"

**MBMJ smiles and sits down.**

"I understand the crown has invested a lot into the agency, and for that I am grateful. But I understand that this was not done in charity. It is a period of investment, which is a necessary requirement for a golden age. You cannot get to Spring without first passing through Winter."

**He looks at The Early Bird.**

"I understand that when you were first getting onto the stage, it was difficult, and touch-and-go. But now, things are good. 

Truly good things cannot happen without this kind of struggle." **MBMJ gives Ageny a stern smile.**

Bennett is stirred at least a bit by your absurd earnestness. "If I may. Have you ever seen a show put on by this federation, Mr. Ageny?"

"Certainly. I went to one a decade ago or so. And I've heard plenty of second-hand accounts of how things function now, and how the event historically worked."

"...That's quite a gap in time."
Bennett/Cent/Bennett

"The time gap isn't the main issue, in my opinion. There's a bigger, uglier fish to fry." **MBMJ shakes his head.**

"You've heard me give you the sauce about our entertainment, so I hope you can intuitively understand that it's perhaps the thing that is serialized and episodic in nature, less like a herd of unorganized cattle, and more like ducks, all in a row."

**He strokes his chin.**

"Now, I'm not the smartest tool in the school, but I would be willing to bet a bit of muscle mass that the vast majority of our ticket-holders are people who have seen previous events, or at the very least, have kept up with the story via outside means. With regular sporting events, and stage shows, I imagine that is not as truly the case.

Think about it this way. If you see a stage show, you have experienced it, and you're done. You only come back when there's another show to see. In that way, the more of them you watch, the less likely you need to go back. But the world we show them is one that isn't told on the scale of hours, but instead on the scale of months. It is something that you become involved in, invested in. Think of someone who shows up to shows for six months. They become acquainted with our people, they see us war, they see us laugh, they see us love... thousands of flies on the walls, cheering us on. From there, it becomes life, and they become citizens of our world. It is *not* an easy world to leave, once you have lived in it for a while. Look at me- do you think I could be like this otherwise?

That is why our service is more sensitive to investment. Once we have people with us, they will stay. We need to have this period of investment, even when other sports, or other performance doesn't. We offer a unique thing to this kingdom, unlike anything else. I hope that is intuitive."
((uh. roll persuasion))
LOL!

"..."
Cent.
"This is him, yes? The face of your brand?"

Bennett chuckles. "Well, not to downplay his accomplishments, but I-"
"Yes." Bruna.

Cent continues. "This charlatan, thi-"
Bruna meets his gaze with an intensity far beyond is appropriate for the setting. According to some, at least. She at least succeeds at the intimidation roll.
"...Whatever. I suppose he's still 'in character'. I won't do anything drastic. But I'll be keeping a close eye on this place starting now."

**MBMJ looks at Bennet, then Docker, then Bruna, then Walt, then back to Cent.**

"I am the conductor of my own mind train, and I can't speak for anybody else's, but I welcome your scrutonious gaze. The more you look at us, the more appreciative and impressed you will certainly be."

"Mm." He leaves.

"Huuuaaaagghghgrhrhugaghh", Walt caps off his presence with. Been holding in that breath a while.

**MBMJ puts his face in his hands and rests his elbows on the table, before he lowers his head to the table.**

"..."

The silence is unanimous.
"Well, I think that oughta count as a success! Thought he'd blow the whole place to smithereens, how stone-faced he came in!" Docker attempts to lighten the mood.

**MBMJ raises his head and looks at Docker.** "I only do what we can. I reckon with his job... I get the unique impression that as soon as he walked in, his mind was made up like a bride on her wedding night... he wasn't gonna let us go without being impressed right up to high heaven."

"...no good."
Bruna's face is all scrunched up.
"That's no good. He's going to give us a *chance*? Like we need him!?"

Walt says actual words again. "W-well, we kind of do, so-"

"I *live* here! In this building! I have nothing without this job! We need to... there has to be something. Can we get him fired?"

"What? No, obviously we just arrange a show that displays why this is a cultural touchstone worth preserving." Bennett.

**MBMJ shakes his head.**

"It's not just. I can't allow myself to win off of chicanery."

**He shakes his head.**

"Besides. It's likely he's only reporting the will of the council he speaks to. The worms regurgitated to us today were ones that were already given to him by his mommy birds. At the very least, the council will be able to piece it together. If someone else can come up with an idea, I would be all ears. But I can only do, well... what I can."

Bruna pauses. "This... this is why I exist. I'll look into it. I'll head into the archives. There's something. There's some answer." She is yiiking out a little, and leaves.

Walt sighs. "The meeting's over, to be clear. You don't have to stay here." He does not move.

"This is my home. You all are my family. If you are asking me if I'd be more comfortable elsewhere than at a family meeting, I wouldn't be. If you're politely asking me to leave the lot of you alone for now, I will gladly depart."
(is this like a telling me to leave pause or a regular pause)
((i forgor!))

Walt smiles. "I appreciate it, Mr. Big Man Junior. The day you joined us... it might've been the most important moment in this establishment's history."

"Hah! You wanna contend, with the-"
"You want to challenge the- No,"
"You want to be a contender, and that's fine. But I hope you can-"
"I hope with you can contend with being tender, because after this match, I'm gonna leave you tender-er."
"Between the two of us, at least we can make a good fighter and a half, but unfortunately, you can't make two halves with a whole, and you can't... you can't... get in with half a ticke-"
"The two of us, we're two halves of a whole, but that hole is only big enough for one wrestler, and I'll have you know that..."
**MBMJ stops and shakes his head.**
**He walks to a mirror.**
"Mister..."
"Big Man..."
"Junior..."

**He poses, putting his hand in front of his face.**

"Aha! Yes, it is I! Mr. Big Man Jr. You think that you can challenge my home, you world-eater? Well, you're welcome to try- but if you want to step in our world, you have to fight by our rules."

"Yes, you surmise quickly, but your fast eyes won't save you from my skill- I'm royalty here, and here, the crown is only given to those with power beyond what your microcosmic brain could understand!"
"Our citizens are kind and fair, but tough! Our warriors have all but the most incredible of power!"
"What do you think even gives you the right? Are you incapable of seeing? Or do you simply not care!"
"Hah! It doesn't even matter. I simply wanted to know about who I am fixing to destroy. You are nothing to me! I'm Mr. Big Man Jr!"
"You are weak in this world! You have nothing!"
"You think you could consume us? Hah! Laughable. What could you even do to try?"
**He looks in the mirror for a moment, before exhaling.**
**He hangs his head.**
**After a few moments, he turns around and begins to continue workshopping lines.**

The cause of that is the energy that flows within them, which a hollow shell has none of. The lookout drone is a more curious case, one that theoretically could ignite, but this is not feasible in practice. Even without my interference, at our altitude, the outside temperature is significantly lower than it would be on the surface, and it never reaches the risk parameters for even older models of comparable scale. All that leaves is the controls for the ship itself. I've never taken them apart, since that would be a foolish idea, but they don't involve flammable energies at all. Every remaining surface is made of stone." She says all of this without pausing. "Do you want to know about the other floors?"

It's finally time to move on from this house. Well, it's not like I'm all too attached to here anyway. And it's not like I'm scared of the outside world, or anything like that. I've just never had any reason to leave. People don't visit the entirety of the planet just because they know they can. Most people probably never even leave the city they were born in. People only do things because they think they have to. I just never had to leave. Everything I needed was here, and I'd never needed anything more. So while it's true I could've just left, and most people would probably have told me I was some kind of awful person for never leaving, I just had no reason to.

People spend their entire lives trying to find meaning in pathetic meaningless lives of poverty. The word is filled with entitled and lazy morons who accomplish nothing in their entire lives. No, from my experience, those types aren't even people. They're servants, deluding themselves into thinking what they think or say matters. I don't fall to such delusions. The meaning of my existence isn't found in pathetic attempts to contribute anything meaningful to the world. In fact, I can already do whatever I want with my money. If I felt the need to overthrow a government that annoyed me, I had the power to do that in a moment. Of course, the concept of a coup is completely ridiculous and moronic. It's just self-aggrandizing terrorism, where you cloak your narcissism and self-righteousness in layers of fearmongering to make yourself seem better. But that's not really my point. I'm far above, by very design of my birth. You could call it 'Fate', I guess, even if that's rather cliche of a description.
